did.abstract: Women's Project (WP) Theater was founded in 1978 by Julia Miles to develop and cultivate the creative talents of women in the American theater. WP Theater sought to give women from all areas of theater the opportunity to establish their professional crediblity, gain visibility and foster their artistic growth. The collection includes play scripts, promotional materials, administrative records, and materials related to Julia Miles, founder and artistic director. WP Theater often comissioned plays by women writers. Playwrights whose work WP Theater produced, either in public rehearsed readings or full productions, make up a significant portation of these records and include those by such widely recognized authors as Cynthia Ozick, Eve Ensler, Paula Giddings,Susan Brownmiller, Gail Sheehy, Judith Viorst, Molly Haskell and Penelope Gilliatt. Also included is a script for Letters Home by Rose Lerman Goldemberg based on Sylvia Plath's Letters Home.
did.langmaterial: The collection is in English, with a few scripts in Vietnamese and Hindi.

accessrestrict.head: Conditions Governing Access
accessrestrict.p: This collection is open for use without restriction beyond the standard terms and conditions of Smith College Special Collections.

acqinfo.head: Immediate Source of Acquisition
acqinfo.p: Donated by Julia and Lisa Miles between 1989 and 2014.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Women's Project (WP) Theater was founded in 1978 by Julia Miles to address the conspicuous underrepresentation of women artists working in American theater. Its purpose was to identify and nurture the work of women-identified playwrights, directors, and actors. It was previously known as The Women's Project, and Women's Project and Productions. The playwrights whose works were produced by WP theater, either in public rehearsed readings or full productions make up a significant portion of these records. They include scripts by include well-known authors including Joyce Carol Oates, Susan Brownmiller, Paula Giddings, Eve Ensler, Wendy Wasserstein, Gail Sheehy, Cynthia Ozick and Molly Haskell.

Under a grant from the Ford Foundation, Miles first created The Women's Project under the umbrella of The American Place Theatre to encourage the development of female playwrights and directors and to provide a forum for their work. For its first nine years, WP Theater staged its productions in the basement of the American Place Theatre and, while there, produced rehearsed readings, studio productions, and, in a few cases, main-stage productions. In 1987, the project left the American Place Theatre and became an independent organization.

Since 1978, WP Theater has produced more than 600 Off-Broadway plays and developmental projects and has partnered with a number of other New York theater companies for co-productions, including Playwrights Horizons and The New Group. Often, WP Theater produces plays that have New York or world premieres. The WP Theater expanded their reach to new audiences and participants by integrating programs such as rehearesd readings for plays in development, residencies, internships for cis, trans* and gender non-conforming playwrights and writing teams, guest workshops, and partnerships with other theater organizations.

prefercite.head: Preferred Citation
prefercite.p: WP Theater records, Sophia Smith Collection, SSC-MS-00361, Smith College Special Collections, Northampton, Massachusetts.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: The WP Theater records came to the Sophia Smith Collection in eight donations from 1989-2014. Parts of the papers arrived foldered and organized, as they had been in the WP Theater offices, but many documents arrived unfoldered and unordered. In organizing the materials, in many cases folder titles were taken from the group's original organization. Other folder titles were created by the processing archivist. Unfoldered materials were roughly sorted and and described so they could be made available for research use.

In January-February 2019, processing was carried out by Madison White, Scott Biddle, and Ellice Amanna. When we came to the collection, it had already been partially processed, so we used the existing structure to determine how we would order the collection. For unprocessed boxes, we separated materials into 3 series: Plays, Administrative Files, and Julia Miles papers. We removed obvious duplicates and sensitive materials. Materials related to education were carefully screened to remove any FERPA protected materials. For materials that we were unsure whether to include in series 1 or 2 (mainly rehearsed readings and festivals) we let the previous work done take the lead. We moved AV and digital materials to their own boxes, but decided to describe them as part of the three series.

Once series had been roughly sorted and duplicates separated, we then started ordering individual series. All series were ordered alphabetically. We refoldered and boxed as needed, mainly when slumping was an issue. Since most folders already had accurate labeling, we decided to keep existing file names and to only rarely separate materials found in one folder. AV materials and posters were ordered in the same way as the collection.

Once the collection had its new arrangement we started on the description, correcting mistakes as we went. Series 1, Plays, were described at the play level, with brief descriptions of the materials in each play's files. Series 2 and 3 were described at the file level. AV and oversize posters and art were described within each series, including extent, format, and content information.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Women's Project (WP)Theater records include play scripts and materials related to play productions, as well as the administrative records of the theater. The scripts in the collection include those by such recognized writers as Cynthia Ozick, Eve Ensler, Paula Giddings, Susan Brownmiller, Gail Sheehy, Judith Viorst, Molly Haskell and Penelope Gilliatt. Also included is a script for Letters Home by Rose Lerman Goldemberg based on Sylvia Plath's letters to her family. Particularly well documented are the theater education program and plays commissioned by WP Theater. Records are divided into three series. Series I contains materials related to plays and productions put on by WP Theater. Included are draft, revised and final scripts; production materials; play development materials; information on rehearsed readings; cast contact lists and directories; advertising; information on directors, composers, and playwrights; costume designs; publicity materials; correspondence; and audiovisual materials such as audio tapes, photographs, VHS tapes, CDs, and slides. The series includes oversize posters, flyers, art work and costume designs. Information on festivals, play series, and plays put on in a particular season can be found in Series II.

Series II contains administrative records, including newsletters, budgets and financial materials, correspondence, board minutes, flyers, costume designs and information on festivals and series, as well as some art work. There are also notes and documents evaluating the quality of scripts that have been submitted by playwrights. Particularly well documented in this series is the WP Theater education program for New York high school students, Ten Centuries of Women Writers. Education materials include curriculum, correspondence, research, student work, and funding records.

Series III contains the personal records of Julia Miles, the founder and longtime artistic director of Women's Project Theater. Her papers include correspondence, information on her acting career, and information on other organizations she was involved with. Her activity in the Women's Forum, her founding of League of Professional Theatre Women, and her involvement with the Four Women Production Company are especially well documented.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: In February, 2019, duplicate ticket stubs from various performances, playbills, newsletters and scripts were removed from the collection and recycled. A few of each of these items were kept before removing the duplicates. Employee and student financial information was also removed and destroyed. Plays and playbills unrelated to Women's Project Theater were discarded.

userestrict.head: Conditions Governing Use
userestrict.p: To the extent that she owns copyright, Julia Miles has assigned the copyright of WP Theater to Smith College; however, copyright in other items in this collection may be held by their respective creators. For reproductions of materials that are governed by fair use as defined under U. S. Copyright Law, no permission to cite or publish is required. For instances which may regard materials in the collection not created by Julia Miles or WP Theater, researchers are responsible for determining who may hold materials' copyrights and obtaining approval from them. Researchers do not need anything further from Smith College Special Collections to move forward with their use.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series I includes play scripts and materials related to rehearsed reading and full productions of those scripts. The scripts in this collection include those by such recognized women writers as Cynthia Ozick, Eve Ensler, Paula Giddings, Susan Brownmiller, Gail Sheehy, Judith Viorst, Molly Haskell and Penelope Gilliatt. Also included is a script, Letters Home, by Rose Lerman Goldemberg, based on Sylvia Plath's letters to her family. Series I contains draft, revised and final scripts; production materials; play development materials; cast contact lists and directories; advertising; information on directors, composers, and playwrights; original costume designs; publicity materials; correspondence; and audiovisual materials such as audio tapes, photographs, VHS tapes, CDs, and slides. The series includes oversize posters, flyers, costue designs and other art work. Information on festivals, play series, and plays put on in a particular season can be found in Series II.
Of particiular interest are notes and documents created during the script selection process, evaluating the quality of scripts submitted by playwrights found throughout.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series II includes materials from the the administration files of WP Theater. These records include newsletters, budgets and financial materials, correspondence, board minutes, education program materials, information on festivals and series, and logs and evaluations of scripts submitted to WP theater. The publicity materials include art work, such as oversize posters and graphic artist's boards. Records are arranged alphabetically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The Mapping Theatrical Territories Festival was WP Theatre's contribution to the 1988 New York International Festival. WP Theatre put on Letters to a Daughter from Prsion and If You Strike the Woman, You Strike the Rock. For the latter play, the theater partnered with the Vusisizwe Players, from Soth Africa. Materials include playbills, scripts, correspondence, scrapbooks, photos, and administrative files.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series III of the WP Theater records consists primarily of the professional papers of Julia Miles, relating to her career as an actress and producer. Materials include photos, articles, correspondence, contracts, planners, press clippings, reviews, script pages, speeches, as well as papers pertaining to the League of Professional Theatre Women, the Women's Forum, and her production company, Four Women Productions. Papers are arranged alphabetically.
